<ArticleLayout
  title="Laundry Dimensions Australia: What to Measure Before You Plan"
  seoTitle="Laundry Dimensions Australia: Washer, Dryer and Layout Guide"
  description="Plan an Australian laundry using real washer and dryer dimensions, door and lid clearance, cavity space, services and a practical measurement checklist."
  category="Laundry"
  faqs={faqs}
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-23"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, baskets and tidy everyday storage"
>
  <p>
    Australian laundries come in many shapes and sizes. A cupboard laundry has different space
    needs from a room with a top loader or a washer and dryer placed next to each other. Start with
    the appliances, then allow for doors, hoses and enough room to use them comfortably.
  </p>
  <p>
    Most front loaders up to 12 kg are designed around a nominal footprint of about 600 mm wide
    and 850 mm high. That is a useful starting point for planning a laundry. Depth varies much
    more between makes and models, so it needs to be checked against the exact machine.
  </p>
  <p>
    A nominal appliance size is not the same as a guaranteed finished opening. An individual
    machine can be slightly narrower than 600 mm, exactly 600 mm or a little wider. Record the
    exact height, width and depth, then check the manufacturer's requirements for hoses,
    ventilation, door opening and service access.
  </p>

  <section aria-labelledby="laundry-dimensions-heading">
    <h2 id="laundry-dimensions-heading">Laundry dimensions at a glance</h2>
    <p class="table-hint">Swipe sideways to compare the full table.</p>
    <div class="comparison-wrap">
    <table class="comparison-table">
      <caption>Common front loader dimensions and the measurements that vary</caption>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col">Measurement</th>
          <th scope="col">Common planning pattern</th>
          <th scope="col">How to use it</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Width</td>
          <td>About 600 mm is common, but the exact body width can sit slightly below, at or above that nominal figure.</td>
          <td>Use 600 mm as a common nominal width, then confirm the selected model before building the opening.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Height</td>
          <td>About 850 mm is a common height for a front loader.</td>
          <td>Use 850 mm as the common nominal height, then check levelling adjustment and any required space above.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Depth</td>
          <td>Depth varies substantially and the published figure may not include every projecting part or connection.</td>
          <td>Check how the maker measures depth and allow for hoses, taps, plugs and anything projecting at the front.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Door open</td>
          <td>The open door can take the total working depth well beyond one metre.</td>
          <td>Keep enough clear floor area for the door, a laundry basket and the person loading the machine.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Installation space</td>
          <td>Clearance and service requirements depend on the model and the way it is installed.</td>
          <td>Use the selected machine's installation instructions rather than adding one generic allowance to every opening.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Treat these as planning patterns only. The exact product sheet and installation instructions
      for the machine being considered remain the source for its dimensions and clearances.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2>Is there a standard laundry size in Australia?</h2>
  <p>
    There is no single useful room width or length for every Australian laundry. A cupboard
    laundry, apartment laundry and separate utility room all need to be planned around the
    appliances, tub, services, doors and the way the household uses the space.
  </p>
  <p>
    For a new installation or a change to services, check the selected appliances' instructions
    and confirm the installation, ventilation, drainage and electrical requirements with the
    relevant qualified installer or tradesperson. Renters should also check proposed changes with
    their property manager before buying or altering fittings.
  </p>

  <h2>Compare water and energy use after checking fit</h2>
  <p>
    Once a washing machine fits the available space and suits the household's load size, use the
    Australian Government's <a href="https://www.waterrating.gov.au/consumers/water-rating-label" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Water Rating Label guide</a>{" "}
    to compare litres per wash, capacity and the cycle used for testing. A higher WELS star rating
    is useful only when the machine's capacity and program also suit the way you wash.
  </p>
  <p>
    The <a href="https://www.energyrating.gov.au/consumer-information/understand-energy-rating-label" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Energy Rating Label guide</a>{" "}
    explains the annual kilowatt-hour figure and its usage assumptions. Compare machines of a
    similar capacity, then consider features, purchase cost, installation and likely use rather
    than treating the star count as the whole decision.
  </p>

  <h2>Observe a full cycle before measuring</h2>
  <p>
    Include every action, not only the appliance footprint. A person needs to approach with a
    basket, open the door or lid, load the machine, reach the controls and remove washing. The
    dryer may need its filter cleaned and both appliances need reasonable access for inspection
    and servicing.
  </p>
  <p>
    If baskets are the obstruction, start with the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/laundry-basket-storage-what-to-sort-before-buying-hampers-or-sorters/">
      basket routine</a>. If wet clothes are waiting for space, address{" "}
    <a href="/guides/laundry-drying-space-what-to-measure-before-buying-airers-or-racks/">
      drying capacity</a>. Storage built around the appliances will not solve a problem at a
    different stage of the wash.
  </p>

  <h2>Record the installed dimensions</h2>
  <p>
    Measure the machine itself and the opening around it. Handles, doors, hoses and connections
    can make an appliance effectively deeper than the cabinet or body suggests. Record:
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>appliance width, depth and height</li>
    <li>the narrowest gaps at the front, middle and back</li>
    <li>space behind for hoses, vents and connections</li>
    <li>tap, drain, power point and filter positions</li>
    <li>the full swing of the loading door or the open lid height</li>
    <li>controls, service panels and cleaning access</li>
    <li>any movement or vibration observed during use</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Compare these measurements with the manufacturer's installation and operating instructions.
    The visible gap is not storage capacity if the appliance requires it for connection,
    movement, ventilation or maintenance.
  </p>
  <p>
    Treat the common 600 mm by 850 mm figure as the appliance footprint, not a universal
    installation rule. An opening that is exactly the same size as the machine leaves no room
    for differences between models or for any clearance the manufacturer requires. Depth is the
    measurement most likely to change, especially once the door, hoses and connections are included.
  </p>

  <h2>Map the opening zone</h2>
  <div class="advice-stack">
    <section>
      <h3>Top loader</h3>
      <p>
        Open the lid fully and measure its highest and furthest points. Allow room to load bulky
        items and keep shelves, bottles and hanging storage out of the lid path.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Front loader</h3>
      <p>
        Mark the door swing on the floor and include the position of a person unloading it. Keep
        any lower filter or access panel reachable and do not park a hamper in that zone.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Dryer</h3>
      <p>
        Check door swing, controls, filters, vents and the manufacturer's clearance and
        ventilation requirements. Storage should not restrict airflow or routine cleaning.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
  <p>
    For a particularly tight cupboard or a laundry within a bathroom, use the guide to{" "}
    <a href="/guides/small-laundry-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-organisers/">
      small laundry storage</a> to protect the shared walkway and door clearances.
  </p>

  <h2>Treat stacking as an appliance installation decision</h2>
  <p>
    Do not assume any dryer can sit on any washing machine. Check both manufacturers'
    instructions, model compatibility, the need for a specified stacking kit and the completed
    height. Controls and filters must remain reachable without unsafe stretching.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage around a stacked pair should come later. It must not compromise ventilation,
    stability, connections or service access. If installation requirements are unclear, seek
    appropriate advice rather than using shelves or cabinetry to improvise support.
  </p>

  <h2>Test a trolley in the side gap from floor to handle</h2>
  <p>
    Measure the narrowest point of the gap at several heights. Skirting, taps and bowed walls can
    reduce a space that looks generous near the front. Then check whether the trolley can roll
    straight out past the room door, machine handle and basket position.
  </p>
  <p>
    Load the proposed trolley on paper. Tall detergent bottles increase the centre of gravity,
    and a very narrow unit can become unstable or difficult to steer. Leave hoses and fittings
    uncompressed and accessible; a trolley that must be emptied to reach a tap is not a good use
    of the gap.
  </p>

  <h2>Use the space above conservatively</h2>
  <p>
    Storage above the machine can suit light cloths, pegs or modest supplies where the lid,
    ventilation and controls remain clear. Check comfortable reach height, wall construction,
    rated loads, fixing instructions and the consequences of anything falling.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep heavy liquid bottles below shoulder height where practical. Renters should confirm
    permission before drilling or installing fixed racks; the guide to{" "}
    <a href="/guides/renter-friendly-laundry-storage-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">
      rental laundry storage</a> offers portable alternatives.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep water, power and maintenance access visible</h2>
  <p>
    Do not conceal taps, hoses, drains, plugs or power points behind fixed storage. Appliances
    and leads showing damage, overheating or water exposure should not be used. The{" "}
    <a href="https://www.electricalsafety.qld.gov.au/electrical-equipment/buying-and-using-electrical-equipment" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
      Queensland Electrical Safety Office</a> advises following manufacturer instructions and
    checking electrical equipment for damage before use.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage is not a workaround for a damaged connection, leaking hose or inadequate power point
    position. Electrical and plumbing work should be handled by appropriately qualified people
    where required.
  </p>

  <h2>Give detergent a safe home away from the machine top</h2>
  <p>
    Bottles left on an appliance can vibrate, leak or obstruct controls. Measure the tallest
    products and store them upright in a stable position that follows their labels and accounts
    for children or pets. Avoid placing heavy liquids high above a person loading the machine.
  </p>
  <p>
    A removable caddy or nearby cupboard may be more useful than forcing another shelf into the
    appliance zone. See the guides to{" "}
    <a href="/guides/cleaning-product-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-cabinets-or-caddies/">
      cleaning product storage</a> and{" "}
    <a href="/guides/laundry-tub-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-under-sink-organisers/">
      storage under the laundry tub</a> before filling the side or overhead gaps.
  </p>

  <h2>Know which clearances should remain empty</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>a top loader lid or front loader door cannot open fully</li>
    <li>dryer vents, filters or manufacturer clearances would be restricted</li>
    <li>taps, hoses, drains or power points would be hidden</li>
    <li>the appliance moves into the proposed storage zone</li>
    <li>a trolley cannot roll out without disturbing connections</li>
    <li>cleaning or service access would require dismantling the setup</li>
    <li>the real problem is basket placement, drying or excess products</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Clear the appliance area before buying. Empty containers, unused cloths and misplaced
    baskets can make it seem as though another organiser is needed when the better result is an
    unobstructed machine.
  </p>

  <h2>Check access before filling a gap</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>watch one complete wash and dry cycle</li>
    <li>measure the installed appliance, connections and full opening zones</li>
    <li>follow manufacturer placement, stacking and ventilation instructions</li>
    <li>keep taps, hoses, filters, drains and power accessible</li>
    <li>test any trolley at its realistic loaded weight</li>
    <li>keep heavy products at a comfortable height</li>
    <li>preserve cleaning, inspection and service access</li>
    <li>leave functional clearance empty when the machine needs it</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Storage around the appliances succeeds when it quietly supports the next load. If it competes with
    a door, connection, vent or person using the machine, the gap was never spare capacity.
  </p>

  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
</ArticleLayout>
